# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1921-chicago-american-giants-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] The **1919 Detroit Stars baseball team** competed in Negro league baseball during the 1919 baseball season.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] In their first year of competition, the Stars won the championship of independent western Negro league clubs.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] While the Seamhead website reports that the team compiled a record of 27–13, the "Game Log" below includes 44 wins based on 1919 games for which contemporaneous newspaper accounts have been located.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] The Stars played their home games at Mack Park in Detroit with a handful of games also played at Navin Field.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] The team was owned by Tenny Blount and led by player-manager Pete Hill who compiled a .396 batting average and .892 slugging percentage.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] The team was established in 1919 by owner Tenny Blount (1873–1934), sometimes also known as "Teddy" Blount, with assistance from Rube Foster who owned the Chicago American Giants.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] Blount was an Alabama native who moved to Detroit in 1913 and became a prominent "numbers man".
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] In addition to the three Hall of Fame inductees, the Stars received strong performances from several other position players.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] First baseman Edgar Wesley, a left-handed hitter from Texas, compiled a .322 batting average and a .610 slugging percentage for the 1919 Stars.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] In 146 at bats, he tallied eight home runs, 21 extra-base hits, and 43 RBIs.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] Joe Hewitt, an infielder from Alabama, led the team with 153 at bats and ranked second with 36 runs scored and third with 36 hits.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] Second baseman Frank Warfield, a Kentucky native, led the team with eight triples.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] Sam Crawford was the team's leading pitcher, compiling a 10–4 record and 2.89 earned run average (ERA).
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] John Donaldson also pitched for the Stars, compiling a 2.33 ERA.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] Donaldson was regarded as one of the greatest pitchers of the era, appearing in approximately 700 games with over 400 wins and 5,000 strikeouts.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] He was voted a first-team member of the 1952 *Pittsburgh Courier* player-voted poll of the Negro leagues best players ever.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] During April and May, the Stars opened the season with a 13-game win streak, including victories over all-white semipro teams.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] In late May, an all-white team from Wyandotte, Michigan recruited Detroit Tigers pitcher Rudy Kallio to start a game against the Stars; the Stars scored eight runs off Kallio.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] The local semipro champion, the Maxwells, lost two games to the Stars in the first half of the season, then recruited major league pitcher Ralph Comstock to start a July 13 games against the Stars.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] With Comstock pitching a strong game for the Maxwells, the Stars lost their first game to a white team by a 4–3 score.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] The Stars played a total of six games with the Maxwells in 1919, winning three games and losing two.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] The Stars' principal rivalry for the western championship of Negro league baseball came from Rube Foster's Chicago American Giants.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] The Giants won two of three in a series played in Chicago in June.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] When the teams met for a series in Detroit in early July, the Stars won three games.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] The also played a seven-game seriesin late July and early August that was billed as the championship series.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] The Stars won five games to take the championship.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] As noted in the "Game Log" below, the Stars also played multiple series with other Negro League teams, including the Cuban Stars, Dayton Marcos from Ohio, and the Hilldale Club from Pennsylvania.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] In the last game of the season, the Murray All Stars recruited Detroit Tigers pitcher Bernie Boland; Boland held the Stars scoreless.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] The following batting and pitching statistics are drawn from the Seamheads web site which appear to be incomplete.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-brooklyn-royal-giants-season] The **1920 Brooklyn Royal Giants baseball team** represented the Brooklyn Royal Giants as an independent during the 1920 baseball season.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-brooklyn-royal-giants-season] The team compiled a 13–7–2 (.636) record and won the Eastern independent championship.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-brooklyn-royal-giants-season] Nat Strong was the team's owner, and John Henry Lloyd was the manager.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-brooklyn-royal-giants-season] The team played its home games at Dexter Park in Queens.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-brooklyn-royal-giants-season] The team's leading pitchers were Harry Kenyon (3–1, 2.65 ERA) and Jesse Hubbard (3–2, 3.19 ERA, 41 strikeouts).
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-chicago-american-giants-season] The **1920 Chicago American Giants baseball team** represented the Chicago American Giants in the Negro National League (NNL) during the 1920 baseball season.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-chicago-american-giants-season] The team compiled a 51–19–2 record (45–15–2 in NNL games) and won the first NNL championship.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-chicago-american-giants-season] Rube Foster was the team's owner and manager.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-chicago-american-giants-season] The team played its home games at Schorling Park in Chicago.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1920 throughout the world.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-in-baseball] All Negro leagues standings below are per MLB and Seamheads.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-in-baseball] This was the first season of organized Negro league baseball.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-in-baseball] The first Negro National League would run for the next decade and is considered to be of major league status.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-in-baseball] The Chicago American Giants, managed by league founder and former player Rube Foster, won the first league pennant.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-in-baseball] A loose confederation of teams were gathered in the East to compete with the West, however East teams did not organize a formal league as the West did.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1921-bacharach-giants-season] The **1921 Bacharach Giants baseball team**, sometimes known as the **Atlantic City Bacharach Giants**, represented the Bacharach Giants as an independent during the 1921 baseball season.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1921-bacharach-giants-season] The team compiled a 44–36–2 (.549) and was recognized as the Eastern independent champion of Negro league baseball.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1921-bacharach-giants-season] Dick Redding was the team's manager and pitcher.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1921-bacharach-giants-season] The team played its home games at Inlet Park in Atlantic City, New Jersey.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1921-bacharach-giants-season] The team's leading pitchers were Dick Redding (16–11, 3.17 ERA, 130 strikeouts) and Red Ryan (7–5, 2.39 ERA, 43 strikeouts).
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1921-boston-braves-season] The **1921 Boston Braves season** was the 51st season of the franchise.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1921-boston-red-sox-season] The **1921 Boston Red Sox season** was the 21st season in the franchise's Major League Baseball history.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1921-boston-red-sox-season] The Red Sox finished fifth in the American League (AL) with a record of 75 wins and 79 losses, 23+1⁄2 games behind the New York Yankees.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1921-chicago-american-giants-season] The **1921 Chicago American Giants baseball team** represented the Chicago American Giants in the Negro National League (NNL) during the 1920 baseball season.
[src:1921-chicago-american-giants-season/1921-chicago-american-giants-season] The team compiled a 55–28–4 record (44–22–2 against NNL opponents) and won the NNL pennant.
